{
  "How many multiple-choice questions are on the APES exam?": "",
  "80": "",
  "100": "",
  "40": "",
  "60": "",
  "Section I of the AP Environmental Science exam contains 80 multiple-choice questions, which students have 90 minutes to complete and which account for 60% of the total exam score.": "",
  "What are the three types of Free-Response Questions (FRQs) on the APES exam?": "",
  "Only short-answer definitions": "",
  "Only calculation-based questions": "",
  "Only essay-format questions": "",
  "Design an Investigation, Analyze an Environmental Problem, and Propose a Solution": "",
  "The APES exam includes three FRQ types that test different skills: designing controlled experiments, analyzing multi-factor environmental problems, and proposing and justifying evidence-based solutions.": "",
  "A well-constructed FRQ response uses which writing framework?": "",
  "Only personal opinions and anecdotes following conventional understanding": "",
  "Claim-Evidence-Reasoning: clear claims backed by specific scientific evidence with logical reasoning": "",
  "Only vocabulary definitions without context when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "Only labeled diagrams, particularly regarding reasoning when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The Claim-Evidence-Reasoning (CER) framework is essential for AP responses because it demonstrates scientific thinking by clearly stating a position, supporting it with specific data or facts, and explaining the logical connection between them.": "",
  "If a city of 500,000 people produces 2 kg of waste per person per day, what is the total daily waste?": "",
  "10,000,000 kg": "",
  "100,000 kg": "",
  "500,000 kg": "",
  "1,000,000 kg (1,000 metric tons)": "",
  "The calculation is straightforward: 500,000 people multiplied by 2 kg per person equals 1,000,000 kg, which is equivalent to 1,000 metric tons of daily municipal solid waste.": "",
  "A population of 10 million with a birth rate of 15 per 1,000 and a death rate of 8 per 1,000 has what growth rate?": "",
  "15 per 1,000": "",
  "23 per 1,000": "",
  "8 per 1,000": "",
  "7 per 1,000 (0.7% per year)": "",
  "The rate of natural increase equals birth rate minus death rate: 15 per 1,000 minus 8 per 1,000 equals 7 per 1,000, or 0.7% per year, not counting immigration or emigration.": "",
  "Using the Rule of 70, how long will it take a population growing at 2% per year to double?": "",
  "140 years": "",
  "20 years": "",
  "70 years": "",
  "35 years": "",
  "The Rule of 70 states that doubling time equals 70 divided by the percentage growth rate, so 70 divided by 2 equals 35 years for the population to double in size.": "",
  "If a coal plant emits 0.9 kg CO2 per kWh and a solar farm emits 0.05 kg CO2 per kWh, how much CO2 is saved by switching 1,000,000 kWh to solar?": "",
  "50,000 kg": "",
  "900,000 kg": "",
  "850,000 kg of CO2": "",
  "The emission savings equal the difference in emission factors multiplied by the energy produced: (0.9 minus 0.05) times 1,000,000 equals 0.85 times 1,000,000 equals 850,000 kg of CO2 avoided.": "",
  "When designing an investigation for an AP FRQ, which elements must be included?": "",
  "Hypothesis, independent and dependent variables, control group, procedure, and data analysis plan": "",
  "Only a hypothesis, particularly regarding controlled based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Only the research question, particularly regarding that when measured under": "",
  "Only the expected conclusion, particularly regarding method when considering": "",
  "A complete experimental design for AP must include all major components of the scientific method, demonstrating the student's ability to plan a valid, controlled experiment that could produce reliable, analyzable data.": "",
  "What is the percent change formula used in AP calculations?": "",
  "Old value minus new value": "",
  "New value minus old value": "",
  "New value divided by old value": "",
  "(New minus Old) divided by Old, multiplied by 100%": "",
  "The percent change formula calculates the relative difference between two values by dividing the absolute change (new minus old) by the original value and multiplying by 100, which is commonly tested in AP quantitative problems.": "",
  "If species count in a habitat drops from 50 to 35, what is the percent decline?": "",
  "35%": "",
  "30%": "",
  "25%": "",
  "15%": "",
  "Applying the percent change formula: (50 minus 35) divided by 50, multiplied by 100 equals 15 divided by 50 times 100, which equals 30% decline in species richness.": "",
  "What is LD50 (lethal dose 50%) in toxicology?": "",
  "The dose at which 50% of a substance evaporates": "",
  "The dose of a substance that kills 50% of test organisms, used to evaluate chemical hazards and compare toxicity": "",
  "The temperature at which 50% of organisms experience heat stress": "",
  "The concentration at which 50% of pollutants are filtered out": "",
  "LD50 is a standard toxicological measure representing the dose lethal to 50% of a test population, allowing comparison of relative toxicity between chemicals and forming the basis of dose-response relationships in environmental health.": "",
  "What is a dose-response curve?": "",
  "A graphical representation of the relationship between the amount of exposure to a substance and the resulting effect on organisms": "",
  "A chart comparing costs and benefits of pollution control": "",
  "A diagram showing energy transfer between trophic levels": "",
  "A graph showing population growth over time": "",
  "A dose-response curve plots the magnitude of biological effect against the dose of a substance, revealing important information such as thresholds, LD50 values, and whether effects are linear or nonlinear.": "",
  "What is an independent variable in experimental design?": "",
  "The variable deliberately manipulated by the researcher to test its effect on the dependent variable": "",
  "A variable that cannot be controlled or predicted": "",
  "A variable that remains constant throughout the experiment": "",
  "The variable that is measured as the outcome of the experiment": "",
  "The independent variable is the factor the experimenter intentionally changes to observe its effect on the dependent variable, and correctly identifying it is essential for earning points on AP 'Design an Investigation' FRQs.": "",
  "What is a control group in an experiment?": "",
  "The group of researchers conducting the experiment": "",
  "The group that determines which variables to measure": "",
  "The group that receives the highest dose of the treatment": "",
  "The group not exposed to the independent variable, serving as a baseline for comparison with experimental groups": "",
  "A control group provides the baseline comparison necessary to determine whether observed effects are actually caused by the independent variable, and including it is required for earning full points on AP experimental design questions.": "",
  "What is a confounding variable?": "",
  "A variable that has no effect on the experiment based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The variable measured as the experiment's outcome under the given assumptions": "",
  "The main variable being tested in an experiment when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "An uncontrolled factor that may influence results and make it difficult to determine whether the independent variable caused the observed effect": "",
  "Confounding variables are uncontrolled factors that can create alternative explanations for results, and addressing them through proper experimental design (randomization, controls, replication) is essential for valid scientific conclusions.": "",
  "What is the AP scoring rubric's approach to awarding points on FRQs?": "",
  "Points are awarded based on response length and writing quality": "",
  "Each point has specific earning criteria requiring correct, relevant information": "",
  "Points are awarded primarily for good handwriting and organization": "",
  "Only vocabulary usage determines the score": "",
  "AP FRQ rubrics use specific point-earning criteria where each scoreable element requires precise, accurate information, meaning students earn points by providing targeted answers rather than writing lengthy, vague responses.": "",
  "What is an externality in environmental economics?": "",
  "The profit margin of an environmental company": "",
  "Government spending on environmental protection": "",
  "A cost or benefit of an economic activity that affects parties not directly involved in the transaction": "",
  "A product sold in foreign markets": "",
  "Externalities are costs (like pollution-related health problems) or benefits (like pollination from nearby forests) imposed on third parties who did not choose to be affected, and they represent a market failure frequently tested on the AP exam.": "",
  "What is the difference between correlation and causation?": "",
  "Correlation can only be negative, while causation is always positive": "",
  "They mean the same thing in scientific studies": "",
  "Correlation indicates two variables change together, while causation means one directly causes the change in the other": "",
  "Causation is always weaker evidence than correlation": "",
  "Understanding the distinction between correlation and causation is critical for AP science because observing that two variables change together does not prove one causes the other; controlled experiments or additional evidence are needed to establish causality.": "",
  "What is a cost-benefit analysis (CBA) in environmental decision-making?": "",
  "A systematic comparison of all costs and benefits of an action, including environmental and social factors, to determine net value": "",
  "A method that always favors the least expensive option": "",
  "A calculation that only applies to government-funded projects": "",
  "A method that only considers financial costs of a project": "",
  "Cost-benefit analysis weighs all costs (including environmental externalities, health impacts, and social disruption) against all benefits (including ecosystem services, public health improvements, and economic gains) to inform environmental policy decisions.": "",
  "What is statistical significance in environmental research?": "",
  "A determination that observed results are unlikely to have occurred by chance alone, typically with less than a 5% probability": "",
  "Results that are important to policymakers": "",
  "Any result that shows a large numerical difference": "",
  "Data that supports the researcher's hypothesis": "",
  "Statistical significance (typically p less than 0.05) indicates the results are unlikely due to random chance, providing confidence that the observed pattern reflects a real effect rather than natural variation in the data.": "",
  "A student is given AP FRQ data showing that a lake's dissolved oxygen dropped from 8 mg/L to 2 mg/L over five years while nearby farmland fertilizer use tripled. The question asks them to design an investigation to test whether fertilizer runoff is causing the oxygen decline. What should their response include?": "",
  "Only a statement that fertilizer causes eutrophication, particularly regarding procedure following the established framework": "",
  "A testable hypothesis, controlled and experimental groups with different fertilizer concentrations, measurement of dissolved oxygen as the dependent variable, and a data analysis plan": "",
  "Only a recommendation to ban all fertilizer use, particularly regarding whether according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Only a graph showing the correlation between the two variables under normal circumstances": "",
  "AP 'Design an Investigation' FRQs require all elements of experimental design: a testable hypothesis linking fertilizer to oxygen decline, identification of variables, a control group, a clear procedure with replication, and how data would be collected and analyzed.": "",
  "An AP question presents data showing that Country A (population 50 million) emits 500 million metric tons of CO2 annually, while Country B (population 1 billion) emits 3 billion metric tons. A student claims Country B is the worse polluter. What critical analytical step are they missing?": "",
  "They should compare the countries' GDP instead": "",
  "They should compare total land area instead of emissions": "",
  "They need to calculate per capita emissions, which shows Country A emits 10 tons per person versus Country B's 3 tons per person": "",
  "They should only look at historical cumulative emissions": "",
  "Per capita analysis is essential for fair country comparisons: Country A emits 10 metric tons per person (500M divided by 50M) versus Country B's 3 metric tons per person (3B divided by 1B), revealing that Country A's citizens have a much larger individual carbon footprint.": "",
  "A researcher wants to determine if a new pesticide harms aquatic invertebrates. She sets up aquariums with identical conditions except varying pesticide concentrations (0, 10, 50, 100, and 500 ppb) and measures invertebrate survival after 96 hours. Which type of relationship is she investigating?": "",
  "Biomagnification through a food chain": "",
  "Demographic transition patterns": "",
  "A dose-response relationship to determine the pesticide's toxicity to aquatic organisms": "",
  "Competitive exclusion between invertebrate species": "",
  "This experimental setup tests the dose-response relationship between pesticide concentration and organism survival, with the 0 ppb aquarium serving as the control and the range of concentrations allowing determination of LD50 and threshold effects.": "",
  "An AP FRQ presents this scenario: a city plans to build a new highway through wetlands to reduce commute times. Students must 'Analyze the Environmental Problem.' Which response would earn the most points?": "",
  "Simply stating that highways are bad for the environment, particularly regarding most under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Only listing the benefits of reduced commute times, particularly regarding scientific following conventional understanding": "",
  "Identifying specific ecosystem services lost (water filtration, flood control, habitat), explaining downstream effects on water quality and biodiversity, and connecting to broader impacts like increased impervious surfaces and urban runoff": "",
  "Only calculating the cost of highway construction, particularly regarding systems when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "High-scoring AP responses identify specific causes and effects, name ecosystem services, explain scientific mechanisms, and connect the project to broader environmental impacts, demonstrating systems thinking rather than superficial analysis.": "",
  "A student's AP FRQ response states: 'Pollution is bad for the environment and should be stopped.' Why would this earn few or no points?": "",
  "The response is too short in word count when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "The statement is factually incorrect when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "The response is too vague, lacks specific scientific evidence, and does not address the particular question asked": "",
  "The student used informal language in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "AP rubrics award points for specific, relevant information tied to the question asked, not general statements. A response must identify the specific type of pollution, its mechanism of harm, affected organisms or ecosystems, and evidence-based reasoning.": "",
  "An AP question asks: 'A community's electricity comes entirely from coal. Propose a solution to reduce their carbon emissions by 50% within 10 years.' What elements must a top-scoring response include?": "",
  "Only listing the environmental harms of coal combustion, particularly regarding must under normal circumstances": "",
  "A specific solution (e.g., transitioning to solar/wind), how it reduces emissions, evidence of its effectiveness, potential trade-offs (cost, intermittency), and justification for why it addresses the 50% target": "",
  "Only naming solar energy as a replacement, particularly regarding comes as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Only stating that climate change is a serious problem, particularly regarding require based on established principles": "",
  "AP 'Propose a Solution' FRQs require naming the specific solution, explaining the mechanism by which it addresses the problem, providing supporting evidence, acknowledging trade-offs, and connecting back to the quantitative goal stated in the question.": "",
  "During the AP exam, a student encounters a multi-part FRQ with parts (a) through (e) but only has 12 minutes remaining. What is the best time-management strategy?": "",
  "Skip the question entirely and review multiple-choice answers": "",
  "Answer the easiest parts first to secure those points, then return to harder parts with remaining time": "",
  "Focus all time on part (a) to write a perfect answer": "",
  "Write a detailed introduction and conclusion for the full question": "",
  "Since each FRQ part is scored independently, answering the easiest parts first maximizes total points earned, and brief targeted answers earn more points than one elaborate response that leaves other parts blank.": "",
  "An AP question provides a table showing energy consumption data for four countries and asks students to calculate which country has the highest per capita energy use. A student gets the arithmetic wrong but shows the correct formula and approach. How would this likely be scored?": "",
  "Most points can still be earned because the correct process and reasoning are shown, even with an arithmetic error": "",
  "Zero points because the final answer is incorrect": "",
  "Points are deducted for every incorrect number in the calculation": "",
  "Full points because showing work is all that matters": "",
  "AP rubrics typically award points for demonstrating correct methodology and reasoning even when arithmetic errors occur, which is why students should always show their work including formulas, setup, and units on quantitative problems.": "",
  "An AP FRQ shows data from two watersheds: Watershed A (forested, low nitrogen runoff of 2 kg/ha/yr) and Watershed B (agricultural, high nitrogen runoff of 25 kg/ha/yr). Both drain into the same estuary. Students must explain why the estuary experiences seasonal dead zones. What is the strongest response?": "",
  "Both watersheds contribute equally to the dead zone formation, particularly regarding watersheds based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The dead zones are caused by thermal pollution from power plants along the estuary under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Agricultural runoff from Watershed B delivers excess nitrogen that fuels algal blooms, and decomposition of dead algae by bacteria consumes dissolved oxygen, creating hypoxic dead zones during warm months when oxygen solubility is already lower": "",
  "The dead zones are natural and unrelated to land use practices, particularly regarding both in most standard conditions": "",
  "This response earns points by using specific data (comparing the 2 vs. 25 kg/ha/yr runoff rates), explaining the eutrophication mechanism step by step, and adding the seasonal temperature-oxygen relationship to demonstrate integrated understanding.": "",
  "A student preparing for the APES exam focuses only on memorizing vocabulary terms and definitions. Their practice FRQ scores remain low. Based on AP scoring principles, what change in study strategy would most improve their performance?": "",
  "Only focus on reading the textbook more thoroughly": "",
  "Memorize more vocabulary terms and scientific names": "",
  "Only practice multiple-choice questions and skip FRQ practice": "",
  "Practice applying concepts to novel scenarios, connecting topics across units, performing calculations, and writing evidence-based responses": "",
  "The APES exam tests applied understanding rather than rote memorization, so the most effective preparation involves practicing with past exam questions, making cross-topic connections, working through calculations, and writing structured responses.": ""
}